39:24.362 --> 39:26.231 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if they were in the similar
circumstance.

39:26.264 --> 39:27.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The precedent was set.

39:28.032 --> 39:32.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the sad part going
forward is,
it used to be, if you were
president, you

39:32.804 --> 39:38.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had some incentive to try to
nominate a judge
who could maybe get 60 votes,
who could appeal

39:38.576 --> 39:40.245 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to some people in the other
party.

39:40.278 --> 39:43.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now you have zero incentive as
long as you
can control the Senate.

39:43.781 --> 39:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so we will see more -- even
more partisan
judges than we do now.

39:47.452 --> 39:51.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only thing I would say to
mitigate, which
I think is a decline and a
degradation and

39:51.222 --> 39:55.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a sadness, is that I have a
feeling that something
is about to happen with the
Trump administration.

39:55.493 --> 39:59.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Either it will shift, or
something bad will
happen, a scandal or something,
and that we're

39:59.731 --> 40:04.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in sort of a pre-apocalypse
phase, or maybe
that's putting it strongly.

40:04.435 --> 40:08.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But history is about to change,
because I
don't think the status quo can
maintain.

40:08.773 --> 40:13.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so if we have something, an
administration
that really suffers some
grievous blow, then

40:13.344 --> 40:16.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Washington culture will have
an opportunity
to change for the better.

40:16.814 --> 40:19.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, as of now, it's a long,
slow slide.

40:19.450 --> 40:22.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do I hear you
forecasting an
apocalypse of some sort?

40:22.654 --> 40:23.621 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

40:23.655 --> 40:24.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, that word
came out.

40:24.656 --> 40:26.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I should have stuck with
acidity.

40:26.090 --> 40:27.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That was a better word.

40:27.492 --> 40:29.227 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

40:29.260 --> 40:31.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: But I do think
Washington -- it
doesn't feel like this
administration can

40:31.396 --> 40:33.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
maintain the current state.

40:33.331 --> 40:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Something is going to happen,
and then we
will be in a different world,
with the possibility

40:36.501 --> 40:38.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of bipartisanship.

40:38.303 --> 40:41.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And some senators, like Senator
Collins and
Coons and others, are still
hungering for

40:41.506 --> 40:42.707 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

40:42.740 --> 40:44.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you see
coming out
of the Senate?

40:44.309 --> 40:48.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: John McCain is
fond of quoting
Chairman Mao.

40:48.046 --> 40:51.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And David brings that to mind,
which is, it's
always darkest just before
everything goes

40:51.316 --> 40:52.283 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
black.

40:52.317 --> 40:53.284 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

40:53.318 --> 40:55.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: And that is what
strikes me.

40:55.153 --> 40:59.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I join him, I join David in
commending Susan
Collins of Maine, the
Republican, and Chris

40:59.724 --> 41:08.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coons of Delaware, the Democrat,
for trying
to keep alive a sense of comity
and -- I-T-Y

41:08.266 --> 41:10.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
-- and rapprochement and
bipartisanship.

41:10.902 --> 41:18.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're sponsoring a resolution
that 61, or
at least a letter that 61
senators have signed

41:18.076 --> 41:26.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they will not have the
nuclear option
on just legislative -- domestic
legislation,

41:26.217 --> 41:30.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that that would keep at
least some hope
alive that there would be a
chance of moving

41:30.822 --> 41:33.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
across the aisle, working across
the aisle.

41:33.458 --> 41:37.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think one of the saddest
moments for me
of the year 2016, Judy, was when
John McCain,

41:37.829 --> 41:42.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who had been the apostle of
bipartisanship,
announced before the election
that he wouldn't

41:42.867 --> 41:48.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vote for any Supreme Court
nominee whom Hillary
Clinton -- President Hillary
Clinton nominated.

41:48.272 --> 41:49.674 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's contagious.

41:49.707 --> 41:53.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Slings and arrows
coming from
both sides.

41:53.277 --> 41:56.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We wish you both a wonderful
weekend.

41:56.047 --> 42:00.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you.

42:00.618 --> 42:10.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields and
David Brooks,
thank you.

42:10.962 --> 42:16.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, as we approach the Jewish
holiday of
Passover, we have a new addition
to the "NewsHour"

42:16.734 --> 42:17.702 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Bookshelf.

42:17.735 --> 42:19.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a celebration of cooking
and tradition.

42:19.704 --> 42:24.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN, Chef: When I
started the book,
I decided I really wanted to go
to India,

42:24.041 --> 42:25.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because I knew there was a
Jewish community
there.

42:25.943 --> 42:32.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I got to the synagogue
in Cochin,
it said that Jews had been
coming from the

42:32.083 --> 42:33.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
time of King Solomon.

42:33.618 --> 42:35.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I thought, wow.

42:35.553 --> 42:41.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And with that,
celebrated food
authority Joan Nathan started
her 11th cookbook,

42:41.459 --> 42:48.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
"King Solomon's Table: A
Culinary Exploration
of Jewish Cooking From Around
the World,"

42:48.366 --> 42:51.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with recipes handed down from
generation to
generation.

42:52.003 --> 42:56.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What you have done in this book
is, you take
us to different parts of the
world.

42:56.307 --> 43:00.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then you show us these
incredible dishes.

43:00.344 --> 43:02.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How in the world did you pull
all this together?

43:02.313 --> 43:06.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: I went to a lot of
places in
the world, but I could find
these immigrants

43:06.784 --> 43:13.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from Azerbaijan and Uzbekistan
in Brooklyn,
or Iranian Jews in L.A.

43:13.558 --> 43:16.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then I found pockets like in
El Salvador,
in Cuba.

43:16.894 --> 43:21.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I found people that told me
about stories
that I had never heard before.

43:21.265 --> 43:26.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How did you
decide which foods
to choose?

43:26.504 --> 43:27.738 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: You know what?

43:27.772 --> 43:30.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I find a really wonderful dish.

43:30.741 --> 43:33.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Then I go with it.

43:33.544 --> 43:39.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For example, I went to an
Ethiopian Jewish
dinner in California.

43:40.017 --> 43:42.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was in San Diego.

43:42.553 --> 43:44.822 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I went to a Shabbat dinner.

43:44.856 --> 43:52.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So they had this dabos, which is
an Ethiopian
Shabbat bread, adapted, of
course, from an

43:52.730 --> 43:54.198 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Ethiopian bread.

43:54.232 --> 43:57.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was so delicious, I thought,
I have got
to put that in the book.

43:57.301 --> 44:00.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And the other
thing that we're
standing in front of is this
flourless chocolate

44:01.005 --> 44:04.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cake, which came out of someone
who came from
Egypt.

44:04.408 --> 44:05.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOAN NATHAN: From Egypt.

44:05.910 --> 44:10.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And, you know, flourless
chocolate cake is
part of our seder every year.

44:10.848 --> 44:18.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't have wheat, or flour
in -- unless
its specially watched flour, in
your desserts.

44:18.222 --> 44:22.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I always liked having a
flourless chocolate
cake.

44:22.293 --> 44:24.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I thought maybe you would
help me decorate
it.

44:24.195 --> 44:25.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good.

44:25.329 --> 44:26.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm going to do a little of this
while you're
talking.

44:26.731 --> 44:27.698 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: That's right.

44:27.732 --> 44:29.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That looks beautiful.

44:29.600 --> 44:34.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been very lucky through
the years that
people have opened up to me all
over the world.

44:34.539 --> 44:39.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And like, for example, I wanted
to get Iraqi
recipes, but I couldn't go to
Iraq.

44:39.043 --> 44:41.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I was told that the best
Iraqi cooks live
in London.

44:41.979 --> 44:47.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I went to London, and I got
a wonderful
Passover macaroon.

44:47.385 --> 44:50.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then somebody told me about
a recipe called
shritzla (ph).

44:50.354 --> 44:55.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was a blueberry bun that
people in
Toronto ate.

44:55.660 --> 44:58.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I learned that it came from
Southwest
Poland.

44:58.062 --> 45:04.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the woman that made it, if
she hadn't
come over very early, my guess
is that that

45:04.068 --> 45:05.836 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
recipe would have been lost.

45:05.870 --> 45:11.309 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In Southwest Poland, the
religious Jews, when
the Nazis came in, they just
took them out.

45:11.342 --> 45:17.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this recipe, I saved a
recipe for other
people, because most people we
killed.

45:17.381 --> 45:20.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, these are stories that
are quite amazing.

45:20.585 --> 45:21.986 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you have kept
them alive.

45:22.019 --> 45:24.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: Well, I have tried
to keep them
alive.

45:24.221 --> 45:28.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have often thought, what's
the difference
between Jewish cooking and other
cooking?

45:28.292 --> 45:31.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, this could be any
immigrant food
in many ways.

45:31.829 --> 45:36.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's Jewish immigrants for,
I think, three
reasons.

45:36.701 --> 45:39.136 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One is because of the dietary
laws.

45:39.170 --> 45:41.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, you can't mix milk and
meat.

45:41.672 --> 45:47.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't eat certain shellfish,
so that what
happens is, Jewish people think
about their

45:47.078 --> 45:48.245 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
food a lot.

45:48.279 --> 45:49.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And they like to eat.

45:49.280 --> 45:50.715 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're obsessed about it.

45:50.748 --> 45:53.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And most food is connected to a
holiday.

45:53.784 --> 45:55.786 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, that's one point.

45:55.820 --> 46:00.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The second is that Jews have
always been merchants,
since the time of King Solomon,
going out

46:00.891 --> 46:02.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
looking for the new.

46:02.960 --> 46:07.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the third is that Jews have
been expelled
from so many places, like so
many people today.

46:08.032 --> 46:11.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they keep -- wherever you
go, you have
to adapt to new food.

46:11.302 --> 46:13.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And they have
kept their traditions
as they have moved.

46:13.671 --> 46:15.006 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: Yes, exactly.

46:15.039 --> 46:17.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let's look
at one of
those traditions now.

46:17.174 --> 46:18.142 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JOAN NATHAN: OK.

46:18.175 --> 46:19.443 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let's go into my dining room.

46:19.477 --> 46:22.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Joan, now we
are at a table
set for seder.

46:22.647 --> 46:24.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOAN NATHAN: Right.

46:24.415 --> 46:28.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Which, of course,
is all around
the Jewish observance of the
Passover.

46:28.085 --> 46:33.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is one of those traditions
where food
is of enormous importance.

46:34.025 --> 46:35.059 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOAN NATHAN: Right.

46:35.092 --> 46:36.127 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is the seder plate.

46:36.160 --> 46:40.364 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the first thing is the
shankbone.

46:40.398 --> 46:46.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is symbolic of the
destruction of
the First and Second Temple, as
is the egg,

46:46.170 --> 46:52.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is also symbolic of
rebirth and general
sorrow.

46:52.743 --> 47:01.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Parsley is the spring, but you
dip it in saltwater
to remember your enemies, even
when you have

47:01.152 --> 47:03.954 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conquered them, because they
have suffered.

47:03.988 --> 47:07.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The other two are the matzah and
the bitter
herbs.

47:07.458 --> 47:09.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: This story, it
goes back to
Abraham.

47:09.860 --> 47:11.595 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: It goes back to
Abraham.

47:11.629 --> 47:18.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But these three symbols, the
bitter herbs,
lamb, and the matzah, were
mentioned in the

47:18.235 --> 47:19.270 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bible.

47:19.303 --> 47:21.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Those were -- the only thing
that was necessary.

47:21.672 --> 47:26.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it wasn't until after the
destruction
of the Second Temple that
Passover became

47:26.977 --> 47:32.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a home festival around a table,
because there
was no longer a temple in
Jerusalem.

47:32.616 --> 47:34.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You have made
some sweet jam.

47:34.819 --> 47:36.854 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: Right, this is a
sweet blend.

47:36.887 --> 47:43.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is symbolic of the mortar
when the Jews
were slaves in Egypt.

47:43.127 --> 47:46.697 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it's all slavery to freedom.

47:46.731 --> 47:49.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the original one was a date
jam.

47:49.767 --> 47:51.235 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: This is this.

47:51.268 --> 47:53.938 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: The biblical honey.

47:53.971 --> 47:57.575 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that was the one in Babylon.

47:57.608 --> 48:04.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then there is -- this one
actually is from
Maine, blueberries, very modern.

48:04.148 --> 48:07.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This one is from Persia or Iran.

48:07.752 --> 48:09.386 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And it has nuts.

48:09.420 --> 48:10.421 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's got pistachios.

48:10.454 --> 48:12.089 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It has pears.

48:12.123 --> 48:14.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's got dates, all kinds of
good things.

48:14.725 --> 48:19.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In Judaism, food
is an integral
part of telling the story.

48:19.130 --> 48:20.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOAN NATHAN: Absolutely.

48:21.031 --> 48:26.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why is it so
important to remember
these stories and to remember, I
mean, down

48:26.871 --> 48:30.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the recipes that you have
preserved in
this book?

48:30.441 --> 48:36.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOAN NATHAN: Well, I think, in
the Bible,
it says you must relate this
story to your

48:36.213 --> 48:42.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
children, so they know that
they're free men
and that they are Jews, and that
you don't

48:42.920 --> 48:47.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
want to be in slavery, and you
don't want
to treat people like slaves.

48:47.892 --> 48:51.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just something that we must
preserve
throughout history.

48:51.095 --> 48:54.565 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the hardest meal for me to
prepare.

48:54.598 --> 49:00.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's the most wonderful, the
most meaningful,
because I do think that it's
important for

49:00.204 --> 49:07.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
families today to take those
traditions from
their past and cling to them.

49:07.211 --> 49:14.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I really get totally moved
when I think
about the seder, with Jews all
over the world

49:14.718 --> 49:22.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the same time reading this
ancient text
and enjoying foods from all over
the world.

