49:53.057 --> 49:57.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Finally tonight: reflections on
coming to
the United States from author
Alia Malek,

49:57.428 --> 50:02.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who considers the various
journeys Syrian
refugees take on their many
roads from Damascus.

50:02.900 --> 50:09.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALIA MALEK, Author: In September
2015, I felt
I had to drop everything and go
to Turkey

50:09.340 --> 50:13.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to report on Syrians as they
hurriedly made
their way to Europe, trying to
beat the rapidly

50:13.344 --> 50:14.912 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
closing borders.

50:14.945 --> 50:19.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a Syrian-American, their fate
was one I
had only accidentally been
spared.

50:19.717 --> 50:24.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As I accompanied them on this
journey, I couldn't
help thinking of how different
their circumstances

50:24.521 --> 50:29.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were from how my own Syrian
family had ended
up in the diaspora, of how my
mother, pregnant

50:29.894 --> 50:32.763 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with me, herself had left
Damascus.

50:32.796 --> 50:36.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Unlike the dangerous
Mediterranean Sea crossings
and the trek through the
Balkans, her trip

50:36.967 --> 50:39.436 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
itself wasn't treacherous, and
it wasn't undignified.

50:39.470 --> 50:44.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was traveling to Baltimore
to join my
father, a medical resident at
the University

50:44.108 --> 50:45.442 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Maryland.

50:45.476 --> 50:48.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
While emotionally painful, her
journey couldn't
have been easier.

50:48.245 --> 50:52.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She wasn't facing imminent death
or displacement,
as people are today.

50:52.650 --> 50:56.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, both my parents meant
to eventually
return to their homeland.

50:56.487 --> 50:59.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when it became clear what
life would be
like under the Assad regime,
they gave up

51:00.024 --> 51:01.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their dream to return.

51:01.992 --> 51:06.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Years after all their children
were born American,
they too finally became
naturalized Americans.

51:06.730 --> 51:12.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When my family arrived here in
the '70s, being
Syrian wasn't a barrier to
becoming American.

51:12.770 --> 51:17.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Even if Arabs weren't
well-perceived generally,
Syrians specifically didn't hold
much of a

51:17.308 --> 51:19.643 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
place in the American
imagination or consciousness.

51:19.677 --> 51:24.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, I remember the best a
schoolyard
bully could do was tell me that,
as a Syrian,

51:24.648 --> 51:26.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I ate too much cereal.

51:26.884 --> 51:29.320 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Oh, for those days.

51:29.353 --> 51:34.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In these past six years, as
Syria has disintegrated,
taken over the headlines, and as
Syrians have

51:34.491 --> 51:39.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
become the foreign menace of the
day, I have
often thought about the vagaries
of fate,

51:39.129 --> 51:44.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of how accidental and unintended
occurrences
are what separate me from the
Syrians unfairly

51:44.268 --> 51:50.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
maligned, banned, and banished
today, how
our lot depends on when we
decided to leave,

51:50.307 --> 51:54.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where we landed, and how we got
there, whether
we boarded flights with regular
tickets and

51:54.878 --> 51:59.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
visas, or were piled on top of
each other
on flimsy rafts and left to
drift across the

51:59.416 --> 52:05.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sea unguided, how our future
depends on what
suffix happens to follow Syrian
on arrival.

52:05.656 --> 52:06.824 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is it refugee?

52:06.857 --> 52:08.592 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is it immigrant?

52:08.625 --> 52:10.127 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is it American?

52:10.160 --> 52:12.229 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm lucky to be that last one.

52:12.262 --> 52:16.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A Syrian mother I was traveling
with across
Europe worried at each new
border, what would

52:16.967 --> 52:18.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
happen to her children?

52:18.869 --> 52:21.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In Syria, they had been
comfortably working
class.

52:21.905 --> 52:24.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Her husband was a baker, and she
was a stay-at-home
mom.

52:24.675 --> 52:28.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the beginning of the trip,
her children
were horrified to have to
relieve themselves

52:28.512 --> 52:30.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
outdoors and in public.

52:30.614 --> 52:34.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Within days, though, she was
pained to see
how they had quickly adjusted to
their new

52:34.485 --> 52:36.353 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
reality.

52:36.387 --> 52:39.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I instead approached each
crossing with a
guilty confidence of a
passport-carrying American.

52:40.024 --> 52:45.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was completely aware that my
fortune was
in large part by chance and
circumstance.

52:45.462 --> 52:50.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, rather than make me unique,
I imagine
that makes me like many other
Americans whose

52:50.868 --> 52:56.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
families were also once upon the
time among
the lucky, favored by fate to
have made it

52:56.607 --> 52:59.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to these shores when and how we
did.

